itle": "Monetary Policy Analysis with Potentially Misspecified Models", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/sept09/20051010_app.pdf", "ex:pages": "1415-50", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Marco Del Negro"}, {"ex:name": "Frank Schorfheide"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "We develop a general equilibrium model in which stock prices of innovative", "ex:volume": "99", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Technological Revolutions and Stock Prices", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/sept09/20051277_app.pdf", "ex:pages": "1451-83", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Lubo Pstor"}, {"ex:name": "Pietro Veronesi"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "We experimentally test an endogenous-timing investment model in which subjects", "ex:volume": "99", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Hindsight, Foresight, and Insight: An Experimental Study of a Small-Market Investment Game with Common and Private Values", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/sept09/20070475_app.zip", "ex:pages": "1484-1507", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Asen Ivanov"}, {"ex:name": "Dan Levin"}, {"ex:name": "James Peck"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "We show that any decision maker who \"narrowly brackets\" (evaluates decisions", "ex:volume": "99", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Narrow Bracketing and Dominated Choices", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/sept09/20071131_app.zip", "ex:pages": "1508-43", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Matthew Rabin"}, {"ex:name": "Georg Weizsacker"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "We compare the most common methods for selling a company or other asset", "ex:volume": "99", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Why Do Sellers (Usually) Prefer Auctions?", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.99.4.1544", "ex:pages": "1544-75", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jeremy Bulow"}, {"ex:name": "Paul Klemperer"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "We study an allocation problem where a set of objects needs to be allocated to agents arriving over time. The basic model is of the private, independent values type. The dynamically efficient allocation is implementable if the distribution of agents' values is known. Whereas lack of knowledge about the distribution is inconsequential in the static case, endogenous informational externalities arise if the designer gradually learns about the distribution by observing present values. These externalities may prevent the implementation of the dynamically efficient allocation. We provide necessary and sufficient conditions for the efficient allocation to be implementable. (JEL D11, D82)", "ex:volume": "99", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Learning about the Future and Dynamic Efficiency", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.99.4.1576", "ex:pages": "1576-87", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Alex Gershkov"}, {"ex:name": "Benny Moldovanu"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "We study ex post efficient policy responses to a run on the banking system and the ex ante incentives these responses create. We show that the efficient response to a run is typically not to freeze all remaining deposits, since doing so imposes heavy costs on some individuals. Instead, once a run is underway, (benevolent) government institutions would allow additional deposit withdrawals, placing further strain on the banking system. When depositors anticipate these extra withdrawals, their incentive to participate in the run increases. In fact, ex post efficient interventions can generate the conditions necessary for a self-fulfilling run to occur. (JEL G21, G8)", "ex:volume": "99", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Bank Runs and Institutions: The Perils of Intervention", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.99.4.1588", "ex:pages": "1588-1607", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Huberto M. Ennis"}, {"ex:name": "Todd Keister"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "This paper examines the efficiency of expectation damages as a breach remedy in a bilateral trade setting with renegotiation and relationship-specific investment by the buyer and the seller. As demonstrated by Edlin and Reichelstein (1996), no contract that specifies only a fixed quantity and a fixed per-unit price can induce efficient investment if marginal cost is constant and deterministic. We show that this result does not extend to more general payoff functions. If both parties face the risk of breaching, the first best becomes attainable with a simple price-quantity contract. (JEL D86, K12)", "ex:volume": "99", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Expectation Damages, Divisible Contracts, and Bilateral Investment", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/sept09/20061292_app.pdf", "ex:pages": "1608-18", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Susanne Ohlendorf"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "In the centipede game, all standard equilibrium concepts dictate that the player who decides first must stop the game immediately. There is vast experimental evidence, however, that this rarely occurs. We first conduct a field experiment in which highly ranked chess players play this game. Contrary to previous evidence, our results show that69 percent of chess players stop immediately. When we restrict attention to Grandmasters, this percentage escalates to 100 percent. We then conduct a laboratory experiment in which chess players and students are matched in different treatments.  When students play against chess players, the outcome approaches the subgame-perfect equilibrium. (JEL C72, C93)", "ex:volume": "99", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Field Centipedes", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/sept09/20071095_app.zip", "ex:pages": "1619-35", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ignacio Palacios-Huerta"}, {"ex:name": "Oscar Volij"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Most analyses of the US Great Moderation are based on structural VARs, and point toward good luck as the main explanation for the recent macroeconomic stability. Based on an estimated New-Keynesian model where the only source of change is the move from passive to active monetary policy, we show that (i) the theoretical VAR innovation variances for all series decrease across regimes; (ii) VAR-based counterfactuals assign a minor role to improved policy; and (iii) VAR impulse-response functions to a monetary shock exhibit little variation across regimes. Our analysis suggests that existing VAR evidence is also compatible with the \"good policy\" hypothesis. (JEL C32, C52, E13, E52, N12)", "ex:volume": "99", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "VAR Analysis and the Great Moderation", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/sept09/20061138_data.zip", "ex:pages": "1636-52", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Luca Benati"}, {"ex:name": "Paolo Surico"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "This paper provides a simple and empirically plausible model of artworks as investment vehicles. It reconciles the observation that average financial returns for collectibles are low and volatile with the theory of consumption-based asset pricing. Art assets are appealing both for their ability to transfer consumption over time and for their use as signals of wealth, as in the literature on the demand for luxuries. Adding art value to utility, returns also reflect this \"conspicuous consumption\" dividend; as a result, average financial returns are low. Risk premia for artworks are predicted to be modest or even negative. (JEL G11, Z11)", "ex:volume": "99", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Art as an Investment and Conspicuous Consumption Good", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/sept09/20071294_app.pdf", "ex:pages": "1653-63", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Benjamin R. Mandel"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "This paper studies the second-moment properties of offshoring, the arrangement whereby firms carry out particular stages of production abroad. It documents a new empirical regularity: maquiladora industries in Mexico that are associated with US offshoring experience fluctuations in employment that are twice as volatile as the corresponding industries in the United States. This finding is not attributable simply to higher volatility in the overall Mexican economy, nor to the smaller size of Mexico's industries compared to US counterparts. (JEL F14, F23, L24, L25, L60, O14)", "ex:volume": "99", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Offshoring and Volatility: Evidence from Mexico's Maquiladora Industry", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/sept09/20070436_data.zip", "ex:pages": "1664-71", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Paul R. Bergin"}, {"ex:name": "Robert C. Feenstra"}, {"ex:name": "Gordon H. Hanson"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "Jan Eeckhout (2004) reports that the empirical city size distribution is lognormal, consistent with Gibrat's Law. We show that for the top 0.6 percent of the largest cities, the empirical distribution is dramatically different from the lognormal, and follows a power law. This top part is extremely important as it accounts for more than 23 percent of the population. The empirical hybrid lognormal-power-law distribution revealed may be characteristic of other key distributions, such as the wealth distribution and the income", "ex:volume": "99", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Gibrat's Law for (All) Cities: Comment", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/sept09/20051005_data.zip", "ex:pages": "1672-75", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Moshe Levy"}]}, {"ex:issue": "4", "ex:abstract": "This reply refutes the objection raised by Levy (2009) about the fit of the upper tail of the city size distribution in Eeckhout (2004). I show that the method on which his conclusion is based is unsubstantiated. The visual interpretation of the fit on log-log plots is misleading. In addition, the methodology used to estimate a truncated subsample of the distribution while testing its significance against a distribution with prespecified parameters is ill-founded. The main conclusion is that Gibrat's law holds: city sizes follow proportionate growth, thus giving rise to a lognormal size distribution, tail included. (JEL R11, R12, R23)", "ex:volume": "99", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Gibrat's Law for (All) Cities: Reply", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/sept09/20071478_data.zip", "ex:pages": "1676-83", "ex:year": "", "ex:date": "2009", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Jan Eeckhout"}]}]